# Hash Table in C

A hash table implemented from scratch in C using **open addressing with linear probing**.  
Built as a learning project — no external dependencies, pure C11.

## Features

- FNV-1a 64-bit hash function
- Open addressing / linear probing for collision resolution
- Automatic expansion (doubles capacity when load factor hits 0.5)
- Generic `void*` values — store any type
- Forward iterator (`hti`) for full table traversal

## File Layout

```
hash_table/
├── src/
│   ├── hash_table.c   # Core implementation
│   └── main.c         # Demo / usage example
├── include/
│   └── hash_table.h   # Public API
├── tests/
│   └── test_hash_table.c
├── .gitignore
├── Makefile
└── README.md
```

## Build & Run

```bash
# Build the demo
make

# Run the demo
./main

# Build and run tests
make test

# Clean build artifacts
make clean
```

## Usage Example

```c
#include "hash_table.h"
#include <stdlib.h>

int main(void) {
    ht *table = ht_create();

    int year = 2010;
    ht_set(table, "Inception", &year);

    int *got = ht_get(table, "Inception");  // → 2010

    ht_destroy(table);
    return 0;
}
```

> **Note:** `value` must not be `NULL` — `ht_get` returns `NULL` to signal "key not found".  
> Heap-allocate values you want to store, and free them before calling `ht_destroy`.

## How It Works

| Operation  | Average | Worst case |
|------------|---------|------------|
| `ht_get`   | O(1)    | O(n)       |
| `ht_set`   | O(1)    | O(n)       |
| `ht_next`  | O(1) amortized | — |

Collisions are resolved by scanning forward linearly until an empty slot is found (linear probing).  
When `size >= capacity / 2`, the bucket array is doubled and all entries are rehashed.

## Planned Improvements

- Deletion with tombstones (field already in `ht_entry`)
- Shrink on low load factor
- Robin Hood hashing (reduces clustering)
- String length caching
- SIMD probing
- Generic typed macros

